✅ Upload a Local Folder to GitHub Using VS Code

=============================================================

1️⃣ Open your project in VS Code

Open VS Code
Click File → Open Folder
Select your project folder

=============================================================

2️⃣ Initialize Git in the folder
Option A: Using Source Control (GUI)
Click the Source Control icon (left sidebar).
Click “Initialize Repository”.

✅Option B: Using Terminal
git init

=============================================================

3️⃣ Add files to Git
GUI:
Click the + icon near each file
OR click “+” next to “Changes” to stage all

✅Terminal:
git add .

=============================================================

4️⃣ Commit your files
GUI:
Type a message in the text box (example: "Initial commit")
Click ✔ Commit

✅Terminal:
git commit -m "Initial commit"

=============================================================

5️⃣ Create a new GitHub repo

Go to: https://github.com/new
Enter repo name
Do NOT add README or .gitignore (optional but avoids conflicts)
Click Create Repository

=============================================================

6️⃣ Connect your VS Code project to GitHub repository

Copy the commands GitHub shows (replace with your repo URL):

✅Terminal:
git remote add origin https://github.com/YOUR_USERNAME/YOUR_REPO.git
git branch -M main
git push -u origin main

=============================================================

7️⃣ Verify upload
Refresh your GitHub repo page—you should see all your files uploaded.

=============================================================
⭐ DONE!

Your local project is now linked to GitHub.
Going forward, just do:

✅Terminal:
git add .
git commit -m "update"
git push
=============================================================